#CriticalThinking

Critical thinking focused curriculua require parsimony.  They must be simple enough for and instructor or pool of instructors to easily implement yet robust enough to overcome the threshold between #AnalyticalThinking and critical thinking.  The rubric must also be general enought to implement across an array of topics, but specific enough that instructor feedback meets the needs of the student's learning.  Curricula whose framework centers around critical thinking as the bone, muscle, and sinew and the course content as the flesh should provide deeper knowledge into a specific facet of the course content the student is interested in and the broad understanding of the course topics.  Unlike a curricula ungirdered by quizzes and tests, the critical thinking program of study askes students to choose a topic of interest they would like to know more about (invoking their #passion), forces them to engage the material from multiple sources and angles, and #interleaves previous topics, future topics, unrelated topics, and new topics.  In short, the complex nature of a critical thinking curriculum provides an ideal platform for student learning in multiple dimensions, but without carful design can quickly become too burdensome on the instructor to be of much benefit to the student.

Parsimony in the critical thinking program of study requires students to learn a unique thinking framework and each subject generally has their own methodologies.  Political science and economics often share a scientific methods (#author #date), while sociology and psychology share another (#author #date).  History and systems engineering provide more diversity to the thinking process.  To each subject their own methodology.  However, essential to any critical thinking program of study is the training and enforced adherance to the field's methods.  Allowing history majors to default to their previously learned history methods may provide a bit of #recall, but it does not place any new demands on the problem solving #neuralPathways (#author #date) that having to learn a new method provides.  Further, the instructor loses the ability to standardize grading between students if strict adherance to the class methods remain uncorrected.

